question.title: ReentrantLock.tryLock(long timeout, TimeUnit unit) does not timeout when can not acquire lock

node.contents: During integration my project with Ehcache (with BlockingCache decorator, which is internally using ReentrantLock) I found some strange behaviour on one machine. From time to time, threads that are waiting for a lock acquisition via ReentrantLock.tryLock(timeout,TimeUnit)-call for time greater than TIMEOUT are not being timeouted (with "false" result). JVM left them behind, and they are block until this lock is released by another thread. In short: from time to time ReentrantLock.tryLock(long timeout, TimeUnit unit) behaves like ReentrantLock.lock().

node.contents: Here is my test code: It starts second thread which holds lock for 5seconds. Main thread tries to acquire it (with timout=50ms). From time to time (it breaks about 14 times for 1000 iterations on the machine) main thread does not timeout after 50ms but waits until second thread releases the lock (=5s).

node.contents: Thanks Evans. It should not make any difference, but I added separate thread that is running in a background and doing something (and now I never unlock the lock). But I have still the same problem ... my thread is in TIMED_WAITING (parking) state for a 20hours... That's really strange. It looks like this is some issue connected with native thread handling by OS (???). It is still nondeterministic and sometimes it works correctly (on other machines it ALWAYS works correctly).

node.contents: A possible explanation can be that after the main process gets the system time and the thread will start to sleep, the system process scheduler removes your process from execution. After 5 seconds, continues execution: thread already slept 5 seconds and the main threads gets the lock. It's kinda strange, though.
